 <h2 class="page-header" id="acronyms"> Acronyms and initialisms</h2>
 <p>Using initialisms can help to make your documents concise. Initialisms (for which you pronounce each letter) include <strong><abbr title="registered retirement savings plan">RRSP</abbr></strong>, <strong><abbr title="tax-free savings account">TFSA</abbr></strong>, and <strong><abbr title="Goods and Services Tax">GST/HST</abbr></strong>. Acronyms (initialisms that you pronounce as words) include <strong><abbr title="registered retirement income fund">RRIF</abbr></strong>, <strong><abbr title="North-American Free Trade Agreement">NAFTA</abbr></strong>, and <strong>GATT</strong>.</p>
 <p>In general, do not assume that your reader knows the meaning of an  initialism. To introduce an initialism into a text or a group of  webpages, write the words in full, followed by the initialism in  parentheses. If your reader may not read your entire text or group of  texts, repeat the introduction in any main section or webpage where you  use the initialism. Be consistent, and avoid switching back and forth  between an initialism and the words it represents.</p>
 <p>You can adjust your use of initialisms to suit particular readers. For instance, if your target audience is <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr> employees, you can omit the full name of the organization and simply use the initialism. </p>
 <h4>Initialisms in titles and headings</h4>
 <p>In general, do not introduce an initialism in a title or a heading. However,  you may want to use an initialism in a title or a heading. In that  case, introduce the initialism in the body of the text by writing the  words in full, followed by the initialism in parentheses.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <p>Section 1.2 &ndash; Contractual joint venture<br />
   In  a contractual joint venture (CJV), the terms, obligations, and  liabilities of the parties are stated in a document signed by both  parties.</p>
  <p>Section 2.4 &ndash; Contributing to your <abbr title="registered retirement savings plan">RRSP</abbr> <br />
   A registered retirement savings plan (<abbr title="registered retirement savings plan">RRSP</abbr>) is designed mainly for saving toward your retirement years. </p>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="addresses">Addresses</h2>
 <p>Preserve formatting by ending all lines with <code>&lt;br&gt;</code>.</p>
 <div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-6">
   <address>
   Mr. John Doe<br />
   Director of Research and Development<br />
   4th Floor<br />
   Business Building<br />
   250 Yonge Street<br />
   Toronto ON  M5B 2L7
   </address>
  </div>
  <div class="col-md-6">
   <pre><code>&lt;address&gt;
  Mr. John Doe&lt;br&gt;
  Director of Research and Development&lt;br&gt;
  4th Floor&lt;br&gt;
  Business Building&lt;br&gt;
  250 Yonge Street&lt;br&gt;
  Toronto ON M5B 2L7
&lt;/address&gt;
</code></pre>
  </div>
 </div>
 <p>The style for addresses was developed to emphasize language quality and readability.  These differ in some respects from the recommendations  published by Canada Post. Please note, however, that Canada Post's  addressing guidelines state that &quot;Canada Post's automated equipment can  decipher a wide range of addressing styles.&quot;</p>
 <p>Write out in full all the elements of an address <strong>except</strong> the <a href="#postal">postal abbreviations for provinces and territories</a>. </p>
 <h3>Addresses: Municipality, province or territory, and postal code</h3>
 <p>Present the municipality, postal abbreviation for the province or the territory, and postal code on the same line. By following this guideline, characters can be optically recognized  and mail will not be diverted for manual processing by Canada Post.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  Ottawa ON K1A 0L5
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>Also refer to <a href="#geographic">Geographic names</a>.</p>
 <h3>Addresses: Capitalization in postal addresses</h3>
 <p>Capitalize the <strong>first letter of every word</strong> in an address except prepositions under four letters (like <strong>of</strong> and <strong>for</strong>), conjunctions under four letters (like <strong>and</strong>), and the articles <strong>the</strong>, <strong>a</strong>, and <strong>an</strong> when they are used within a name or title.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  Mr. John Doe<br />
  Director of Research and Development<br />
  4th Floor<br />
  Business Building<br />
  250 Yonge Street<br />
  Toronto ON  M5B 2L7
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>Also capitalize a <strong>country name</strong>, which should appear alone on the last line of the address block.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  Mr. Alberto Garcia-Alvarez<br />
  Don Remundo 13, Piso 1<br />
  Seville<br />
  SPAIN
  </address>
 </div>
 <h3>Addresses: Punctuation</h3>
 <p>Use punctuation when it is part of a proper name, such as in &quot;St. John's&quot;.</p>
 <p>Use a <strong>comma</strong> to separate two elements on the same line.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  Mr. John Jones<br />
  Director, Marketing Department<br />
  ABC Company <br />
  Site 6, Compartment 10<br />
  Rural Route 3, Station Main<br />
  Maillarville AB  T0L 1K0
  </address>
 </div>
 <h3>Addresses: Official languages in addresses</h3>
 <p>For information on official languages in addresses, see item 10.14 in <a href="http://btb.termiumplus.gc.ca/tpv2guides/guides/tcdnstyl/index-eng.html?lang=eng">The Canadian Style</a> and item 8.1.4i) of <a href="http://btb.termiumplus.gc.ca/tpv2guides/guides/redac/index-eng.html?lang=eng">Le guide du r&eacute;dacteur</a>.</p>
 <p>You may translate these types of thoroughfare: <strong><em>rue</em></strong> (Street), <em><strong>avenue</strong></em> (Avenue), and <em><strong>boulevard</strong></em> (Boulevard).</p>
 <p>When an address such as <em><strong>180, avenue de la Cath&eacute;drale</strong></em> is translated, capitalize it in accordance with English usage:</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  Rimouski Tax Services Office<br />
  Suite 101<br />
  180 De la Cath&eacute;drale Avenue<br />
  Rimouski QC  G5L 5H9
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>When an <strong>ordinal number precedes the word <em>rue</em>, <em>avenue</em>, or <em>boulevard</em></strong> <em>(2e Rue)</em>,  do not translate it. In accordance with French addressing, include a  comma after the building number, superscript part of the numeral <em><strong>(1re, 2e, 5e)</strong></em>, and capitalize the first letter of <em><strong>Rue</strong></em>, <em><strong>Avenue</strong></em>, or <em><strong>Boulevard</strong></em>, which is the official name of the thoroughfare.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  Mr. Paul Truman<br />
  4687, 5e Rue<br />
  Montr&eacute;al QC  H1Y 3N5
  </address>
 </div>
 <h3>Addresses: Gender (Ms., Mrs., Miss, or Mr.)</h3>
 <p>Most <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr> systems indicate  the gender of the person to whom you write. Use Ms., Mrs., Miss, or Mr.  followed by the individual's first name and last name.</p>
 <p>When you do not know the gender, use the person's full name.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Brooke J. Donovan</li>
   <li>J. Doe</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>When the addressee is a woman, and her preference cannot be ascertained, use Ms. </p>
 <h3>Addresses: Additional  guidelines</h3>
 <p><strong>Order the elements</strong> of an address from small to big: floor, building, street, etc.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  4th Floor<br />
  Connaught Building<br />
  555 MacKenzie Avenue<br />
  Ottawa ON  K1A 0L5
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>Write <strong>ordinal numbers in regular characters</strong> (3rd, 7th). Be aware that in Microsoft Word, the superscript effect of ordinal numbers is automatic (3rd, 7th) and <strong>should be cancelled</strong> under Format, Font, Effects. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  340 3rd Avenue
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>If the official name of the <strong>thoroughfare starts with a regular</strong> (125 Street) <strong>or ordinal number</strong> (5th Avenue), <strong>do not use a hyphen</strong> between the civic number and the number of the thoroughfare.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  17 125 Street, 260 5th Avenue
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>Put the <strong>post office box</strong> on the line above the municipality.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  Post Office Box 12075<br />
  St. John's NL  A1B 4R5
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>If there is no unit designator (for example, apartment, suite, unit), use <strong>one space before and after the hyphen</strong> that separates the unit number (see 100 below) and the civic number (1620).</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  100 - 1620 Dickson Avenue
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>If you know it, <strong>do not drop the unit designator</strong> (for example, apartment, suite, unit) and put it above the civic number and the street name.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  Suite 10<br />
  9700 Jasper Avenue
  </address>
 </div>
 <p>Write as <strong>one word compass directions consisting of two points</strong> (Southwest, Northeast)</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <address class="mrgn-bttm-0">
  645 Murray Avenue Southwest
  </address>
 </div>
