 <h2 class="page-header" id="bold">Bold</h2>
 <p>Use bold to emphasize words that need to stand out in a sentence. Use   bold sparingly, otherwise its affect is diminished. You can also use   bold:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>on links on a web page</li>
  <li>to indicate steps in a procedure (see the section &ldquo;Procedures&rdquo;).</li>
  <li>indicate GUI elements in software or specific locations on a website.</li>
 </ul>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <p> Go to <strong>Start &gt; Programs &gt; Word</strong> and select the <strong>Word icon.</strong></p>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="capitalization">Capitalization</h2>
 <p>Capitalization practices vary widely, and writers often question  which words and phrases require caps. The trend in English writing is  toward less capitalization, which is known as a <strong>down style</strong>. We recommend following this style and limiting the use of capital letters. </p>
 <p>Capitalize only the following:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>the first letter of the first word in a sentence or heading;</li>
  <li>acronyms and initialisms; and</li>
  <li>proper nouns.</li>
 </ul>
 <h3>Capitalization: Headings and titles</h3>
 <p>A <strong>heading</strong> may introduce a topic within a document  or on a webpage, or it may identify a column or row in a table. For a  heading, capitalize only the first letter of the first word and any  proper nouns.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Example</h4>
  <h4>Headings and page structure</h4>
 </div>
 <p>A <strong>title </strong>is the official name of a document or  publication, such as a form, guide, policy, act, regulation, or report.  For a title, capitalize the first letter of each word except internal  prepositions of fewer than five letters (such as <strong>of</strong>, <strong>for</strong>, and <strong>with</strong>), conjunctions (such as <strong>and</strong> and <strong>or</strong>), and the articles <strong>the</strong>, <strong>a</strong>, and <strong>an</strong>. </p>
 <ul>
  <li>Guide 5013-G, <em>General Income Tax and Benefit Guide for Non-Residents and Deemed Residents of Canada</em></li>
  <li><em>Annual Report to Parliament, 2009</em><em>&ndash;</em><em>2010</em></li>
  <li>Public Affairs and Communications Policy</li>
 </ul>
 <h3>Capitalization: Proper nouns</h3>
 <p>A <strong>proper noun</strong> is the official name of a particular person, place, or thing.</p>
 <p>For a proper noun, capitalize the <strong>first letter of every word</strong> except internal prepositions of fewer than five letters (such as <strong>of</strong>, <strong>for</strong>, and <strong>from</strong>), conjunctions (such as <strong>and </strong>and <strong>or</strong>), and the articles <strong>the</strong>, <strong>a</strong>, and <strong>an</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>the Access to Information and Privacy Directorate</li>
   <li>the Board of Management</li>
   <li>the Speech from the Throne</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>A proper noun has one form, singular or plural.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>My Account</li>
   <li>First Nations</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h4>Capitalization: Proper noun best practices</h4>
 <p>Any part of a proper noun is not itself a proper noun when it stands alone or modifies another noun.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li><em>Employment Insurance Act</em>, employment insurance, employment insurance premiums</li>
   <li><em>Old Age Security Act</em>, old age security, old age security pension</li>
   <li><em>Universal Child Care Benefit Act</em>, universal child care benefit, universal child care benefit amount</li>
   <li>the Access to Information and Privacy Directorate, an access-to-information request</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>When a noun can have both a singular and a plural form, do not consider it as an official name and do not capitalize it.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>business number, business numbers</li>
   <li>end-state pre-qualification process, end-state pre-qualification processes</li>
   <li>tax-free savings account, tax-free savings accounts</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Capitalization: Institutions and government bodies</h3>
 <p><strong>Capitalize</strong> the proper names of institutions and government bodies</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Public Service Commission of Canada </li>
   <li>Ottawa Carleton District School Board </li>
   <li>Canadian Medical Association </li>
   <li>First Baptist Church </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Capitalize </strong>the proper names of branches, regions, and offices, as well as directorates, divisions, sections, units, and committees.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Winnipeg Tax Services Office </li>
   <li>Jonqui&egrave;re Tax Centre </li>
   <li>Legislative Policy and Regulatory Affairs Branch </li>
   <li>Prairie Region</li>
   <li>Scientific Research and Experimental Development Directorate </li>
   <li>Electronic Commerce Compliance Division</li>
   <li>Process Improvement and Notices Section</li>
   <li>Small Business Advisory Committee</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>But when you make a general reference, <strong>use lower case</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>one of our tax services offices </li>
   <li>your tax centre </li>
   <li>our branches and regions </li>
   <li>each directorate </li>
   <li>the federal public service </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Capitalization: Generic nouns</h3>
 <p><strong>Capitalize</strong> a generic noun when it is used as <strong>a short form</strong> for a proper noun that has been presented in full and that refers to an organization or group of <strong>people</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>The Canadian Medical Association has updated its policy on third-party forms. You can find the policy on the Association's website. </li>
   <li>We work for the Professional Practices Division. The Division has 75 employees.</li>
   <li>We  will consult the Agency Management Committee about this issue at its  next meeting. The Committee is scheduled to meet again in September. </li>
   <li>The  Department of Finance Canada is recommending legislative changes. The  Department will inform us when the recommendations are ready for review.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>But,  lower case short forms for the same proper nouns when they are preceded  by an indefinite article, a possessive adjective, or a demonstrative  pronoun or when they are used as adjectives or are pluralized.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>The Canadian Medical Association has updated its policy on third-party forms. An association making such a change should publicize it widely. </li>
   <li>We work for the Professional Practices Division. This division has 75 employees.</li>
   <li>We  will consult the Agency Management Committee about this issue at its  next meeting. We can make a presentation after outstanding committee  business has been concluded. </li>
   <li>The invitation list  includes the Department of Finance Canada and the Department of  Employment and Social Development Canada. We would like to have  representatives from the departments at the meeting.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Lower case short forms for proper nouns naming things, including programs, initiatives, strategies, and frameworks.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>The  Volunteer Income Tax Program is now in its tenth year. We attribute the  program's success to the enthusiasm of our volunteers.</li>
   <li>The  Board of Management Oversight Framework has been in place since the  2003&ndash;2004 fiscal year. The framework will be reviewed in the 2011&ndash;2012  fiscal year.</li>
   <li>Take some time to read the Sustainable Development Strategy. The strategy will help us reduce waste and save valuable resources.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Capitalization: Copyrighted names</h3>
 <p><strong>Capitalize</strong> trade names of manufactured products.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Plexiglas </li>
   <li>Tylenol </li>
   <li>Xerox</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Some industries use capital letters within the name of a product. <strong>Capitalize</strong> all names of products and terms, including computer language, according to the manufacturer's preference:</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Microsoft Word </li>
   <li>MasterCard</li>
   <li>BlackBerry </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Capitalization: Title of office or rank</h3>
 <p><strong>Capitalize </strong>civil, military, religious, and  professional titles, as well as titles of nobility when they precede  and form part of a personal name.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Prime Minister Stephen Harper</li>
   <li>Finance Minister James Flaherty</li>
   <li>Queen Elizabeth II </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>But<strong> do not</strong> capitalize titles in the plural or titles preceded by an indefinite article or possessive adjective </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>lieutenant-governors of Quebec and Ontario</li>
   <li>assistant commissioners and other members of the Agency Management Committee</li>
   <li>a member of Parliament</li>
   <li>your member of Parliament</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Capitalize</strong> formal titles that follow a personal name.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Sandra Lavigne, Assistant Commissioner, Public Affairs Branch</li>
   <li>The Honourable Rob Nicholson, Minister of Justice</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <p>But<strong> do not </strong>capitalize titles that follow a personal name if they only identify a profession.</p>
  <ul>
   <li>Jane Tanaka, professor of physics</li>
   <li>James Hill, publisher </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Capitalize</strong> a title when it refers to an individual or is used as a substitute for that individual's name</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>The Minister is scheduled to speak before the OECD on Friday.</li>
   <li>In the first of a planned series of announcements, the Commissioner unveiled a new direction for communications.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>But <strong>do not</strong> capitalize a title when it refers to a role that may be held by more than one person over a period of time.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Example</h4>
  <p>To complete the process, the commissioner delivers the annual report to the minister of national revenue.</p>
 </div>
 <h3>Capitalization: Parts of a form or publication</h3>
 <p><strong>Capitalize</strong> references to specific parts of a document</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Appendix D </li>
   <li>Chart 5 </li>
   <li>Figure 1 </li>
   <li>Volume 9</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Capitalize</strong> cross-references to a particular section.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>More titles are listed in the Bibliography. </li>
   <li>See the Appendix for more charts.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> capitalize the word <strong>section</strong> when it is used as part of a law or a set of regulations (see the guideline on <a href="#legislation">Legislation</a> for information on capitalizing references to legislation)</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Example</h4>
  <p>under subsection 12 of section 4 of the Act</p>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> capitalize words such as <strong>page</strong>,<strong> box</strong>, <strong>code</strong>, <strong>line</strong>, <strong>note</strong>,<strong> paragraph</strong>, and <strong>column</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>enter the amount from column 1 on line 421 </li>
   <li>box 14 of the T4 slip </li>
   <li>code 33 in the &quot;Other information&quot; area </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> capitalize generic or non-standard references to our forms and publications.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Example</h4>
  <p>your provincial or territorial tax credits form</p>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="english">Canadian English</h2>
 <p>Canadian English mixes elements of British and American English. Our  pronunciation and spelling tend to be more diverse. We use the <em>Canadian Oxford Dictionary</em> as our principal reference on matters of spelling. You may also want to consult<em> Editing Canadian English</em>, which has a handy set of charts that are a good reference on variations in Canadian spelling.</p>
 <p>Set the spell checker on your computer and in your electronic  documents for Canadian English. But remember that your spell checker  can only tell you if the words you typed are correctly spelled, not if  you typed the correct word. For example, a good Canadian English  dictionary can help you choose between <strong>licence</strong> and<strong> license</strong>, <strong>principle </strong>and<strong> principal</strong>, and <strong>practice </strong>and <strong>practise</strong>.</p>
 <p>Here is a brief list of some commonly accepted Canadian English spellings:</p>
 <ul>
  <li><strong>cheque</strong> not <strong>check</strong></li>
  <li><strong>centre</strong> not <strong>center</strong></li>
  <li><strong>traveller</strong> not <strong>traveler</strong></li>
  <li><strong>organization </strong>not<strong> organisation </strong></li>
  <li><strong>honourable</strong> not <strong>honorable</strong></li>
  <li><strong>defence </strong>not<strong> defense</strong></li>
 </ul>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="commas">Commas</h2>
 <p>Consult <em>The Gregg Reference Manual</em> and 7.13 to 7.21 of <a href="http://btb.termiumplus.gc.ca/tpv2guides/guides/tcdnstyl/index-eng.html?lang=eng">The Canadian Style</a> for general guidance on using commas, and make sure to apply the following aspects of <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr> comma style.</p>
 <h3 id="serial">Commas: Serial comma</h3>
 <p>Use the A, B, and C (A, B, or C) serial comma structure when you list items in a sentence. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Several  federal departments are involved, including Fisheries and Oceans  Canada, Health Canada, and Public Works and Government Services Canada.</li>
   <li>Contact us to get help accessing My Account, NETFILE, Quick Access, or Represent a Client. </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3 id="offsetting">Commas: Offsetting commas</h3>
 <p>Use two commas to set off the title of a form or publication when it appears in the body of a sentence.<br />
 </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Fill out Form TD1, <em>Personal Tax Credit Return</em>, and send it to us. </li>
   <li>For more information, see Guide RC4027, <em>Doing Business in Canada - <abbr title="Goods and Services Tax">GST</abbr> /<abbr title="Harmonized Sales Tax">HST</abbr> Information for Non-Residents</em>, or contact the International Tax Services Office.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Use two commas to set off the year when it follows the month and day.<br />
 </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>On May 29, 2004, there will be a general meeting for all <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr> managers.</li>
   <li>The June 27, 1997, issue of <em>Time</em> had an excellent article on the new technologies developed throughout the twentieth century.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Omit the commas when only the month and year are given.<br />
 </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>We will publish the guide in August 2006 or soon after.</li>
   <li>She published an article on botanical gardens in the July 1998 issue of <em>Canadian Living</em>.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="Contractions">Contractions</h2>
 <p>Contractions can give an informal tone to a document, and they are  often used in promotional material such as posters and advertisements.  You can use <strong>not</strong> contractions (don't, can't, won't, and isn't) and <strong>is</strong> contractions (we're, she's, it's). Do not use contractions for <strong>had</strong>, <strong>have</strong>, <strong>should</strong>, and <strong>would</strong> (you'd, he'd, we've).</p>
 <p>Do not use contractions in formal writing such as publications, correspondence, and reports. </p>
 <p>Be sure not to confuse <strong>its</strong> (the possessive form of <strong>it</strong>) with <strong>it's</strong> (the contraction of <strong>it is</strong>). </p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="currency">Currency</h2>
 <p>Use the following symbols to differentiate between Canadian and U.S. currency in English-language text:</p>
 <p>CAN$1,000</p>
 <p><abbr title="United States">US</abbr>$1,000</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="dash">Dashes and hyphens</h2>
 <p>Use the long <strong>em dash</strong> (&mdash;) to emphasize a break in a  sentence or to present information that is secondary to the main idea  (for example, details about or comments on something in the main  sentence). Em dashes can replace commas, semicolons, colons, or  parentheses in a sentence. Do not include a space before or after an em  dash. In Microsoft Word, you can create an em dash with the command <strong>Alt 0151</strong>.</p>
 <ul>
  <li>On December 31, 2009, you had residential ties&mdash;as defined in the previous section&mdash;in more than one province or territory.</li>
  <li>You  must report your world income&mdash;income received from all sources inside  and outside Canada&mdash;but not all of that income may be taxed in Canada. </li>
  <li>The  director general thanked us for our hard work and congratulated us on  eliminating the backlog of files&mdash;a major accomplishment!</li>
 </ul>
 <p><strong>Note: </strong> In French texts, the spacing around em dashes differs: insert one space before and one space after an em dash.</p>
 <p>Use the shorter <strong>en dash</strong> (&ndash;) in titles of publications that contain two parts or that appear to have a title and  subtitle. Insert one space before and one space after the en dash. In  Microsoft Word, you can create an en dash with the command <strong>Alt 0150</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>For information on how to fill out the return, see Guide T4012, <em>T2 Corporation &ndash; Income Tax Guide</em>. </li>
   <li>Please fill out and keep in your organization's books and records <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pbg/gf/gst29/README.html">Form GST29, Educational Services &ndash; Election and Revocation of the Election to Make Certain Supplies Taxable</a>.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>To save print space, you can also use an en dash to separate a heading from text that follows it.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Remittance requirement &ndash; Under proposed changes, if you  exercise your stock options after 2010, your employer will be required  to withhold and remit an amount for your taxable stock option benefit. </li>
   <li>Section 1 &ndash; Identification </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Use a <strong>hyphen</strong> (-), without spaces before or after it, in some <a href="#Hyphenating">compound terms</a> and in some words with prefixes (such as co-, pre-, re-, semi-, and non-). In Microsoft Word, you can create a non-breaking hyphen by pressing the <strong>Ctrl</strong>, <strong>Shift</strong>, and <strong>hyphen</strong> (-) keys at the same time.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>co-operate</li>
   <li>pre-retirement</li>
   <li>re-establish</li>
   <li>semi-annual</li>
   <li>non-resident</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>If you are unsure whether a particular word with a prefix requires a hyphen, consult a Canadian dictionary. </p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="date">Date and time</h2>
 <h3>Date</h3>
 <p>Use this <strong>alphanumeric form</strong> of dating: month-day-year.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Example</h4>
  <p>September 24, 2009</p>
 </div>
 <p>The number is cardinal (24) and not ordinal (24th).</p>
 <p>In the order month-day-year, the day and year are separated by a comma, and the year should be followed by a comma within a sentence. The spaces should be non-breaking. You can create a non-breaking space by pressing, at the same time, the <strong>Ctrl</strong> and <strong>Shift</strong> keys and the <strong>space bar</strong>. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Example</h4>
  <p>On April&nbsp;16,&nbsp;1985, certain additional provisions of the Charter took effect. </p>
  <p>Code: <code>April&amp;nbsp;16,&amp;nbsp;1985</code></p>
 </div>
 <p>The <strong>all-numeric form</strong> of a date may be appropriate for chronological files and for documents  that are presented in both official languages. The format below  conforms to the <a href="http://publiservice.tbs-sct.gc.ca/fip-pcim/man_pdfs-eng.asp">Federal Identity Program Manual</a> (1.2 Message: Identification of programs and services). The year, month, and day are separated by a non-breaking space or non-breaking hyphen.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Example</h4>
  <p>2009 09 24 <strong>or</strong> 2009-09-24 (September 24, 2009)</p>
 </div>
 <h3>Time</h3>
 <p>To indicate time, write a number based on a 12-hour clock, followed by the abbreviation <strong><abbr title="before midday">a.m.</abbr></strong> or <strong><abbr title="after midday">p.m.</abbr></strong> When stating an hour without minutes, omit the colon and zeroes after  the figure. However, if stating a range of time where one portion  includes minutes and the other does not, add the colon and zeroes to  state the hour.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>The presentation will begin at 1 <abbr title="after midday">p.m.</abbr></li>
   <li>The course runs from 8:30 <abbr title="before midday">a.m.</abbr> to 4:00 <abbr title="after midday">p.m.</abbr></li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>To indicate time within a particular time zone, place a comma after  the stated time and write the name of the zone out in full, with an  initial capital letter.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>The regional directors' teleconference is scheduled for 3 <abbr title="after midday">p.m.</abbr>, Eastern time.</li>
   <li>The  Pacific Region is taking the lead on this file. The director will  deliver a progress report at our next meeting, which will be on  Tuesday, December 18, 2011, at 11:15 <abbr title="before midday">a.m.</abbr>, Pacific time.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>To indicate duration, where possible, spell out <strong>hour</strong> and <strong>minutes</strong>. In tables or in circumstances where abbreviations are necessary, use <strong>h</strong> for hour and <strong>min</strong> for minutes.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>You have 1 hour and 30 minutes to complete this section of the test.</li>
   <li>Time to complete: 1 h 30 min </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h4>Time: Stating time in French </h4>
 <p>Different rules apply in French.</p>
 <p>Use a 24-hour clock. To indicate the hour, place an <strong>h</strong> after the number. When needed, write <strong>min</strong> to record minutes and s to record seconds. A non-breaking space should appear between the number and the <strong>h</strong>, <strong>min</strong>, and <strong>s</strong>. </p>
 <p>When not recording seconds, exclude both <strong>min</strong> and <strong>s</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>La r&eacute;union est pr&eacute;vue pour 13 h 30.</li>
   <li>Il a couru le marathon en 4 h 23 min 30 s.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>For numbers between 1 and 9, you can choose whether to include the zero</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Le train est entr&eacute; en gare &agrave; 8 h 09. <strong>or </strong>Le train est entr&eacute; en gare &agrave; 8 h 9.</li>
   <li>L'avion a d&eacute;coll&eacute; &agrave; 18 h 05. <strong>or</strong> L'avion a d&eacute;coll&eacute; &agrave; 18 h 5.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>If stating an hour without minutes, omit the zeroes:</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>8 h <strong>not </strong>8 h 00</li>
   <li>17 h <strong>not</strong> 17 h 00</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Only use colons to state time in tables (for example, 14:05:32).</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="examples">Examples</h2>
 <p>Sometimes it is a good idea to use an example to show the reader how  a rule or guideline applies. When you prepare these examples, use names  that represent the diversity of ethnic groups in Canada.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="faqs"><abbr title="Frequently asked questions">FAQ</abbr>s</h2>
 <h4>Questions</h4>
 <ul>
  <li>Personalize the questions&mdash;phrase them as though you are the person asking.
   <ul>
    <li>For example, write: &quot;How do I claim the rebate?&quot; <strong>not</strong>: &quot;How is the rebate claimed?&quot;</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Make sure that each question is something people are genuinely likely to ask.</li>
  <li>Remember that users scan FAQs for key words. Use the terms your readers are likely to look for.</li>
  <li>Write each question to stand alone. Follow-up questions should appear separately.</li>
  <li>Ask each question directly, without unnecessary details.</li>
  <li>Avoid putting questions in quotation marks.</li>
 </ul>
 <h4>Answers</h4>
 <ul>
  <li>Personalize your answers&mdash;speak to the person who asked the question.
   <ul>
    <li>For example, if the question begins with &ldquo;I have tuition expenses,&rdquo; then the answer should begin with: &quot;You can&quot; ...<strong>not:</strong> &quot;The student must&quot; ...</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Start the answer with <strong>yes </strong>or <strong>no </strong>if you can and then explain any details.</li>
  <li>Answer only the question asked, and keep the response as succinct as possible. Do not provide extra information.</li>
  <li>Avoid putting answers in quotation marks.</li>
 </ul>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="form">Forms and publications</h2>
 <p>When you refer to a form or publication for the first time, always give its descriptor, its letter-number identifier followed by a comma, and its title. Place an <a href="#offsetting">offsetting comma</a> or a period after the title, depending on whether the reference appears  in the body or at the end of the sentence. Do not include the  offsetting comma or the period in italicized or hyperlinked type.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4>Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Fill out Form TD1, <em>Personal Tax Credits Return</em>, and send it to us.</li>
   <li>See <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pub/tg/t4037/README.html?=slnk">Guide T4037, Capital Gains</a>.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>How you format the descriptor, letter-number identifier, and title of a form or publication depends on whether your document will appear in print form (including <abbr title="Portable document format">PDF</abbr>)  or on the web. If your document will appear in both print and  electronic forms, you must verify that the document's references to  forms and publications are properly formatted for each medium.</p>
 <h3>Forms and publications: Print documents</h3>
 <p>For a first reference in a print document in <strong>Microsoft Word</strong> or <strong>web <abbr title="Portable document format">PDF</abbr></strong>, italicize the title of the form or publication. </p>
 <p>Examples of a first reference in a print or <abbr title="Portable document format">PDF</abbr> document:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>Fill out Form TD1, <em>Personal Tax Credits Return</em>, and send it to us. </li>
  <li>More information is available in Guide RC4027, <em>Doing Business in Canada &ndash; <abbr title="Goods and Services Tax">GST/HST</abbr> Information for Non-Residents</em>. </li>
  <li>For more information, see Pamphlet P151, <em>Canadian Residents Going Down South</em>. </li>
  <li>To learn more, get Information Circular IC07-1, <em>Taxpayer Relief Provisions</em>.</li>
 </ul>
 <p>For later references within a print or <abbr title="Portable document format">PDF</abbr> document, use only the descriptor and letter-number identifier and do not restate the title. For example:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>You can find Form TD1 under &ldquo;Forms and publications&rdquo; on our website.</li>
  <li>Guide RC4027 clarifies how the <abbr title="Goods and Services Tax">GST/HST</abbr> applies to goods imported by non-residents. </li>
 </ul>
 <h3>Forms and publications: Web documents</h3>
 <p>For a <strong>hyperlinked</strong> first reference in a document that will appear on the web, include the descriptor, the letter-number identifier, and the title in the link. Do not italicize the title:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>Fill out <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pbg/tf/td1/README.html">Form TD1, Personal Tax Credits Return</a>, and send it to us. </li>
  <li>See <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pub/tg/t4037/README.html">Guide T4037, Capital Gains</a>.</li>
  <li>Fill out <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pbg/tf/5000-s4-5/README.html">Schedule 5, Details of Dependant</a>, and attach it to your return. </li>
 </ul>
 <p>For later references to the same document or form, use only the descriptor and letter-number  identifier (for example, Form TD1 or Guide T4037) and do not restate  the title. Do not link the second reference unless it is more than one  scroll down the page from the first reference.</p>
 <p>For information on how to format references to <strong>websites</strong> or <strong>webpages</strong> that start with <strong>www.</strong>, see the guideline on <a href="#web">web addresses</a>.</p>
 <h3>Forms and publications: Lists of publications</h3>
 <p>When you list forms and publications, present them in the following  order (unless you feel it is important to list the most used product  first):</p>
 <ul>
  <li>guides </li>
  <li>pamphlets </li>
  <li>forms </li>
  <li>schedules </li>
  <li>all other publications </li>
 </ul>
 <h3>Referring to publications</h3>
 <p>Use <strong>get</strong> rather than <strong>obtain</strong> when advising a reader to find a form or publication&mdash;whether online, by telephone, or in person.</p>
 <ul>
  <li>To permit another person to represent you, get <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pbg/tf/t1013/README.html">Form T1013, Authorizing or Cancelling a Representative</a>. </li>
  <li>Get Form RC4288, <em>Request for Taxpayer Relief</em>, and send it and all supporting documents to your tax services office or tax centre.</li>
 </ul>
 <p>When referring readers to a publication or form, we recommend using <strong>see</strong> rather than <strong>read</strong> or <strong>consult</strong>. </p>
 <ul>
  <li>For details, see Form T2201, <em>Disability Tax Credit Certificate</em>. </li>
  <li>For more information, see <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pub/tg/rc4135/README.html">Guide RC4135, Home Buyers' Plan (HBP)</a>.</li>
  <li>To find out what to report on line 315, see page 40 of the <em>General Income Tax and Benefit Guide</em>.</li>
 </ul>
 <p>However, if you want to emphasize a message about reading, use the verb <strong>read</strong>.</p>
 <ul>
  <li>By being prepared, you will help us serve you better. Before contacting us, read the information included in the <em>General Income Tax and Benefit Guide</em>. </li>
  <li>If  you tell us about an amount you failed to report, we may waive these  penalties. Read &ldquo;What is a voluntary disclosure?&rdquo; on page 11. </li>
  <li>For more details, read the section in Chapter 2, &ldquo;Tax on <abbr title="registered retirement savings plan">RRSP</abbr> excess contributions,&rdquo; in <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pub/tg/t4040/README.html">Guide T4040, <abbr title="registered retirement savings plan">RRSP</abbr>s and Other Registered Plans for Retirement</a>. </li>
 </ul>
 <p>For more information, go to the terminology decision <a href="http://infozone/english/r1713497/writerstoolbox/terminology_archives-e.html#p22">See, read, consult, get, and obtain</a>.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="geographic">Geographic names</h2>
 <p>Use the English name of a province or territory in English texts,  but do not translate the names of cities. For example, the cities  Montr&eacute;al, Qu&eacute;bec, and Trois-Rivi&egrave;res have only one spelling. In other  words, use:</p>
 <ul>
  <li><strong>Qu&eacute;bec</strong> for the city (not Quebec City); and</li>
  <li><strong>Quebec</strong> for the province.</li>
 </ul>
 <p>For more information, see Chapter 15 of <a href="http://btb.termiumplus.gc.ca/tpv2guides/guides/tcdnstyl/index-eng.html?lang=eng">The Canadian Style</a>.</p>
 <p>Also see <a href="#italics">Italics</a>.</p>
