    <ul class="list-unstyled mrgn-lft-lg lst-spcd">
     <li><a href="../design/headings-en.html">Headings<span class="wb-inv"> - Design guide</span></a></li>
    </ul>
    <h3 class="h4"><span class="fa fa-wheelchair text-muted"></span> Accessibility guide</h3>
    <ul class="list-unstyled mrgn-lft-lg lst-spcd">
     <li><a href="../accessibility/headings-en.html">Headings<span class="wb-inv"> - Accessibility guide</span></a></li>
    </ul>
   </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mrgn-lft-md mrgn-rght-md">
   <p>Good headings and subheadings help guide readers through your  document. At a glance, they can see what type of information you are  presenting and where to find the information they need. Since some  users skim through a document by navigating its headings, it is  important to use them appropriately to convey document structure. </p>
   <p>Make sure your headings and subheadings are short, concise, and give a clear idea of the content of the text that follows. </p>
   <p>Headings in the form of questions are effective in drawing readers'  attention. Question headings can be useful in documents written to  promote programs or give information.</p>
   <ul>
    <li>What is the Canada child tax benefit?</li>
    <li>Do I qualify?</li>
   </ul>
   <p>However, for documents outlining processes and procedures, statement headings may be more appropriate.</p>
   <ul>
    <li>Building trust to promote compliance</li>
    <li>Resolving taxpayer disputes and service complaints </li>
   </ul>
   <p>Order your headings and subheadings properly, and do not skip  heading levels (for example, by going from a level 1 heading directly  to a level 3 heading). </p>
  </div>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="hyphenating">Hyphenating compound terms</h2>
 <p>When using <strong>compound adjectives</strong>, hyphenate:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>an adjective and a noun that form a unit to modify another noun:<br />
   <ul>
    <li>a part-time job; a long-term investment </li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>an adjective and participle compound used before <strong>or</strong> after the noun:<br />
   <ul>
    <li>a smooth-talking salesman; the salesman was smooth-talking</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>a compound made up of an adjective and a noun with an <strong>ed</strong> ending:
   <ul>
    <li>able-bodied; short-handed</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>a compound adjective made up of a preposition and a noun:<br />
   <ul>
    <li>out-of-province benefits; in-service training</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>a  phrase that consists of more than two words, at least one of which is  an adverb or a preposition, where the words are used as adjectives:<br />
   <ul>
    <li>the cost-of-living index; on-the-job training</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>a number, a noun, and an adjective that modify a noun:
   <ul>
    <li>a 10-storey-high building, a 31-year-old Canadian resident </li>
   </ul>
  </li>
 </ul>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> hyphenate:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>verb-adverb combinations used as a verb phrase:
   <ul>
    <li>phased in; make up; follow up</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>proper nouns used as adjectives:
   <ul>
    <li>a Privy Council decision</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>proper adjectives combined with a simple modifier:
   <ul>
    <li>a New York chartered bank</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>French or foreign words used as adjectives:
   <ul>
    <li>a priori reasoning</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>words in quotation marks:
   <ul>
    <li>a &quot;zero tolerance&quot; approach</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
  <li>adverbs that end in <strong>ly</strong>:
   <ul>
    <li>richly embroidered; fully employed</li>
   </ul>
  </li>
 </ul>
 <h3>Hyphenating: Carry forward/Carry back</h3>
 When using either of these as a verb (as in <strong>to carry forward</strong> or <strong>to carry back</strong>) or as a noun (as in <strong>a carryback</strong> or a <strong>carryforward</strong>), <strong>do not</strong> use a hyphen. However, when using them as compound adjectives, as in <strong>a carry-forward amount</strong>, use a hyphen.
 <p><strong>Common-law/Common law</strong><br />
  According to the <em>Canadian Oxford Dictionary</em>, when <strong>common-law</strong> refers to marriage, you should always write it with a hyphen.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>A relation also includes a common-law partner.</li>
   <li>They are living common-law.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>The unhyphenated term <strong>common law</strong> refers to law derived from custom and judicial precedent rather than statutes. So you can be &ldquo;living common-law in a common law jurisdiction.&rdquo;</p>
 <h3 id="toll">Hyphenating: Toll free/Toll-free</h3>
 <p>Do not hyphenate this phrase when it is used as an adverb, but do hyphenate it when it is used as an adjective.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>You can call us toll free 24 hours a day.</li>
   <li>Call our toll-free hotline for more information. </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3 id="prefixes">Hyphenating: With prefixes</h3>
 <p>Use a hyphen if adding a prefix to a word might result in mispronunciation (for example, <strong>re-enter </strong>instead of <strong>reenter</strong>) or a change in meaning of the word (for example, <strong>re-cover</strong> instead of <strong>recover</strong>, <strong>re-form</strong> instead of <strong>reform</strong>, or <strong>pre-serve</strong> instead of <strong>preserve</strong>).</p>
 <p><strong>Special rules</strong>: Use the non-hyphenated <strong>online</strong> instead of <strong>on-line </strong>and <strong>email</strong> instead of <strong>e-mail</strong>.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="italics">Italics</h2>
 <p>Italics are difficult to read. <strong>Do not</strong> use italics to highlight or emphasize terms. Use <a href="#Bold">bold</a> instead.</p>
 <h3>Italics: Forms and publications</h3>
 <p>Use italics for the proper titles of <a href="#form">forms and publications</a>:</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Guide RC4070, <em>Guide for Canadian Small Businesses</em></li>
   <li>Pamphlet T4131, <em>Canadian Residents Abroad</em></li>
   <li><a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/E/pbg/tf/t2201/">Form T2201, <em>Disability Tax Credit Certificate</em></a></li>
   <li><em>General Income Tax and Benefit Guide</em></li>
   <li>Form T1248 Schedule D, <em>Information About Your Residency Status</em></li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Italics: Acts and regulations</h3>
 <p>The first time you refer to an act or regulations, put the title in italics.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>paragraph 14(3)(b) of the <em>Income Tax Act</em></li>
   <li>the <em>Income Tax Regulations</em></li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>If you refer to the same legislation later in the same document and do not refer to other legislation, use the word <strong>Act</strong> or <strong>Regulations</strong> as a short form. The word should begin with a capital letter but should <strong>not</strong> be in italics.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <p>According to the <em>Income Tax Act</em>, the CRA may deem  a charitable organization to be exempt from taxes. However, the Act  also permits the CRA to revoke any such exemption.</p>
 </div>
 <p>For more information on how to refer to acts and regulations, see the guideline on <a href="#legislation">legislation</a>.</p>
 <h3>Italics: Foreign words</h3>
 <p>When possible, avoid using words and phrases from other languages in  your documents. If you must include a term from another language, put  that term in italics. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Bryan A. Garner states that the adjective <em>inter vivos</em> can be replaced by <strong>living</strong>, as in the term <strong>living trust</strong>. </li>
   <li>You have translated the phrase <strong>to take advantage of</strong> as <em>prendre avantage de</em>. Most sources suggest that this is an anglicism.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>However, do not put the names of businesses or organizations in italics, even if those names are in another language.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Aluminerie Alouette</li>
   <li>Revenu Qu&eacute;bec</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="legislation">Legislation</h2>
 <p>When you refer to an act for the first time, write the name in full and in italics.  Be sure not to italicize the article <strong>the</strong> before the title of an act.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <ul>
   <li><em>Income Tax Act</em></li>
   <li><em>Employment Insurance Act</em></li>
   <li><em>Income Tax Regulations</em></li>
   <li>The <em>Income Tax Act</em> and the <em>Excise Tax Act</em> contain taxpayer relief provisions.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Writing the name of the act or acts in full and in italics  throughout your document ensures that your reader knows what  legislation you are referring to.</p>
 <h3>Short forms</h3>
 <p>In the same section or chapter of a print document or in the same  webpage (maximum two or three screens), you can use a short form after  you have referred to an act in full and in italics. However, if you  doubt that your readers will remember what act you are talking about,  write the name of the act in full and in italics. </p>
 <p><strong>Use</strong> the word <strong>Act</strong> as a short form if you refer to one act, such as the <em>Income Tax Act</em> or the <em>Employment Insurance Act</em>. Capitalize the letter <strong>A</strong> but do not put the word <strong>Act </strong>in italics. The same format applies to the short form for the <em>Income Tax Regulations</em>. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>We use <strong>taxpayer </strong>in the context of administering and enforcing the <em>Income Tax Act</em>. The term is defined in subsection 248(1) of the Act. </li>
   <li>The <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr> does not publish the <em>Income Tax Regulations</em>. The Regulations are available, however, on the Department of Justice Canada website.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <div class="alert alert-warning">
  <h4>Note</h4>
  <p> In French, we write in italics the equivalent short form, <em>Loi</em> or <em>R&egrave;glement</em>.</p>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> introduce the short form <strong>(the Act)</strong>, written between parentheses and preceded by the article <strong>the</strong>. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Incorrect example </h4>
  <p>We have identified specific areas of non-compliance with the <em>Income Tax Act </em>(the Act). In accordance with section XX of the Act ...</p>
  <div  class="mrgn-bttm-lg"></div>
  <h4>Correct example</h4>
  <p>We have identified specific areas of non-compliance with the <em>Income Tax Act</em>. In accordance with section XX of the Act &hellip;</p>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Use</strong> abbreviations as a short form, such as ITA for <em>Income Tax Act</em> and ETA for <em>Excise Tax Act</em>,  if you refer to more than one act in the same document. Remember,  however, that your readers may be confused if you use several  abbreviations. </p>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> italicize or put periods in the abbreviations, such <em>as</em> <em>ITA </em>or I.T.A. for the <em>Income Tax Act</em> and <em>EIA</em> or E.I.A. for <em>Employment Insurance Act</em>. You will find the correct abbreviations in the <a href="http://infozone/english/r1713497/writerstoolbox/cra_glossary/menu-e.asp">CRA glossary</a> and in <a href="http://btb.termiumplus.gc.ca/tpv2alpha/alpha-eng.html?lang=eng">TERMIUM Plus&reg;</a>.</p>
 <h3>Legislation: Parts of acts and regulations</h3>
 <p>There are different symbols and words to identify the parts of acts and regulations.</p>
 <p>12(1)(a)(iii)(B)(VI)1</p>
 <ul>
  <li>12 section
   <ul>
    <li>(1) subsection
     <ul>
      <li>(a) paragraph [the symbol is a lower case letter of the alphabet]
       <ul>
        <li>(iii) subparagraph [small Roman numeral]
         <ul>
          <li>(B) clause [upper case letter of the alphabet]
           <ul>
            <li>(VI) subclause [large Roman numeral]
             <ul>
              <li>1 sub-subclause</li>
             </ul>
            </li>
           </ul>
          </li>
         </ul>
        </li>
       </ul>
      </li>
     </ul>
    </li>
   </ul>
  </li>
 </ul>
 <p>Use the proper word to identify the part you refer to.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example </h4>
  <p>The term taxpayer is defined in subsection 248(1) of the <em>Income Tax Act</em>.</p>
 </div>
 <p>Write in <strong>regular character</strong> and <strong>between parentheses</strong> the <strong>lower case letter </strong>of the alphabet that identifies a paragraph of an act or regulations. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example </h4>
  <p>Under paragraph 47(1)(b) of the <em>Income Tax Act</em>, the taxpayer &hellip;</p>
 </div>
 <p>We adopted the regular character for consistency and efficiency. In  the legislation, the lower case letter identifying a paragraph appears  sometimes in italics and sometimes in regular character. </p>
 <div class="alert alert-warning">
  <h4>Note</h4>
  <p> In French, write in italics and with a closing parenthesis the lower case letter of the alphabet that identifies a paragraph (<em>alin&eacute;a</em>) of an act or regulations. French writers, editors, and translators use this style consistently.</p>
 </div>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example </h4>
  <p>Selon l'alin&eacute;a 47(1)<em>b</em>) de la <em>Loi de l'imp&ocirc;t sur le revenu</em>, le contribuable...</p>
 </div>
 <h3>Legislation: Capitalization</h3>
 <p><strong>Capitalize</strong> the word <strong>act</strong> when you use it to replace the full name of the act you just wrote in full.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <p>We use taxpayer in the context of administering and  enforcing the Income Tax Act. The term is defined in subsection 248(1)  of the Act.</p>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Do not capitalize</strong> the word <strong>act</strong> when it is used in a general sense or when it is used in plural.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>The Income Tax Act is an act of Parliament that... </li>
   <li>The Access to Information and Privacy Directorate is responsible for fulfilling the <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr>'s responsibilities under the Access to Information Act and the Privacy Act. Taxpayers can make a request under these acts.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> capitalize words such as section, subsection, and paragraph when they are used to identify the parts of acts or regulations.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="line">Line identifiers</h2>
 <p>Use Arabic numerals (1, 2, 3) to identify lines on a form. If you  have to identify lines in subcalculations, use the following order:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>Arabic numerals</li>
  <li>capital letters</li>
  <li>lower-case Roman numerals (place one bracket to the right of each numeral)</li>
 </ul>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <p>_______ 1<br />
   _______ 2</p>
  <p class="mrgn-lft-lg"> _______ A<br />
   _______ B </p>
  <p class="mrgn-lft-xl"> _______ i)<br />
   _______ ii) </p>
 </div>
 <p>You can use bold to highlight a line identifier when it appears  beside a line in a calculation, but do not use bold when it appears  within text. Never use quotation marks or parentheses to highlight  identifiers.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="lists">Lists </h2>
 <div class="row">
  <div class="pull-right col-md-4">
   <div class="well">
    <h2 class="h3 mrgn-tp-0">Related </h2>
    <h3 class="h4"><span class="fa fa-font text-muted"></span> Writing guide</h3>
    <ul class="list-unstyled mrgn-lft-lg lst-spcd">
     <li><a href="../writing/principals-en.html#lists">List principals<span class="wb-inv"> - Writing guide</span></a></li>
    </ul>
    <h3 class="h4"><span class="fa fa-picture-o text-muted"></span> Design guide</h3>
    <ul class="list-unstyled mrgn-lft-lg lst-spcd">
     <li><a href="../design/lists-en.html">Lists<span class="wb-inv"> - Design guide</span></a></li>
     <li><a href="../design/listgroup-en.html">List group<span class="wb-inv"> - Design guide</span></a></li>
     <li><a href="../design/pills-en.html">Pills<span class="wb-inv"> - Design guide</span></a></li>
    </ul>
    <h3 class="h4"><span class="fa fa-wheelchair text-muted"></span> Accessibility guide</h3>
    <ul class="list-unstyled mrgn-lft-lg lst-spcd">
     <li><a href="../accessibility/tables-en.html">Tables<span class="wb-inv"> - Accessibility guide</span></a></li>
    </ul>
   </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mrgn-lft-md mrgn-rght-md">
   <p>If you have a long sentence that contains a number of elements, you  can make the information easier for your reader to understand by  presenting it in a vertical list. In general, use bullets for the items  in lists. Use numbers only when you are providing step-by-step  instructions or when you want to rank or show the priority of items. </p>
   <p>To create an effective list, do the following:</p>
   <ul>
    <li>Begin with a lead-in that introduces or applies to all the list items.</li>
    <li>Include in the lead-in any word or phrase that is common to all the items.</li>
    <li>Put only one idea in each item.</li>
    <li>Use hollow bullets for items in a nested list (a list within a list) to distinguish them from the items in the primary list.</li>
    <li>Punctuate appropriately.</li>
   </ul>
   <p>Avoid creating a <strong>sentence sandwich</strong> where part of your sentence comes before the list and another part comes after.</p>
   <p>Although vertical lists can be useful, do not overuse them. If you  only have one or two points in a sentence, you generally should not  create a vertical list.</p>
   <p>Introduce a vertical list with a colon. While  this colon will precede every vertical list, there are several ways to <strong>punctuate</strong> the items. You can:</p>
   <ul>
    <li>use <strong>semicolons</strong> after each item (and a  period after the final item) when together they complete a sentence  begun by the lead-in and the last two are linked by <strong>and</strong> or <strong>or</strong> to emphasize the relationship between the items; </li>
    <li>use <strong>periods</strong> when each item is a complete sentence and you want it to stand alone; or </li>
    <li>present <strong>without punctuation</strong> a simple list of stand-alone items.</li>
   </ul>
   <p>How you <strong>capitalize</strong> items depends on how you  punctuate them. Capitalize the first letter of the first word of an  item when the item forms a complete sentence and is punctuated with a  period. Do not capitalize the lead words in lists where the items are  not punctuated or are punctuated with semicolons.</p>
   <h3>Lists: Parallel structure </h3>
   <p>All items in a list must be presented in parallel structure.  Parallel structure means maintaining the same grammatical pattern for  each item, such as beginning each with the same part of speech and  using the same verb tense, sentence or phrase structure, voice, and  perspective. For example, if the first item in a list uses the  imperative (or command) mood, all of the items must use the imperative  mood. Or, if your first item begins with a noun, continue listing items  beginning with nouns rather than verbs. Similarly, do not include a mix  of negatively and positively phrased items.</p>
   <div class="well">
    <div class="row">
     <div class="col-md-6">
      <h4>Example of non-parallel structure <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-remove-circle"></span></h4>
      <p>To draft a high quality source document:</p>
      <ul>
       <li>organize your ideas;</li>
       <li>only use short sentences and paragraphs;</li>
       <li>do not use the passive voice; and</li>
       <li>use the right words; </li>
      </ul>
     </div>
     <div class="col-md-6">
      <h4>Example of parallel structure <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-ok-circle"></span></h4>
      <p>To draft a high quality source document:</p>
      <ul>
       <li>organize your ideas;</li>
       <li>write short sentences and paragraphs;</li>
       <li>use the active voice; and</li>
       <li>use the right words; </li>
      </ul>
     </div>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="links">Links</h2>
 <div class="row">
  <div class="pull-right col-md-4">
   <div class="well">
    <h2 class="h3 mrgn-tp-0">Related </h2>
    <h3 class="h4"><span class="fa fa-font text-muted"></span> Writing guide</h3>
    <ul class="list-unstyled mrgn-lft-lg lst-spcd">
     <li><a href="principals-en.html#links">Link principals<span class="wb-inv"> - Writing guide</span></a></li>
    </ul>
    <h3 class="h4"><span class="fa fa-picture-o text-muted"></span> Design guide</h3>
    <ul class="list-unstyled mrgn-lft-lg lst-spcd">
     <li><a href="../design/links-en.html">Links<span class="wb-inv"> - Design guide</span></a></li>
    </ul>
    <h3 class="h4"><span class="fa fa-wheelchair text-muted"></span> Accessibility guide</h3>
    <ul class="list-unstyled mrgn-lft-lg lst-spcd">
     <li><a href="../accessibility/links-en.html">Links<span class="wb-inv"> - Accessibility guide</span></a></li>
    </ul>
   </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mrgn-lft-md mrgn-rght-md">
   <p>Use hyperlinks to provide access to more detailed information. You can hyperlink:</p>
   <ul>
    <li>Web addresses for websites or webpages</li>
    <li>sections of websites or webpages </li>
    <li>documents</li>
    <li>descriptive words and phrases</li>
   </ul>
   <p>Do not place hyperlinks in quotation marks or bold, and  ensure that spaces and punctuation before and after a hyperlink are not included in the hyperlink. </p>
   <p>There are two link types:</p>
   <ul>
    <li><strong>general</strong> links to a Web page &mdash; attempt to match the link text to the <strong>&lt;h1&gt;</strong> on the landing page. </li>
    <li><strong>specific</strong> links to a point on a Web page (anchor point) &mdash; attempt to match the link text to the natural heading (for example an<strong> &lt;h2&gt;</strong>)   on the landing page.</li>
   </ul>
   <p>To avoid confusing the user, <strong>only make minor link text adjustments when</strong>:</p>
   <ul>
    <li> <strong>a link forms part of a sentence</strong>, and maintaining the  &lt;h1&gt; text of   the landing page (or anchor point) creates an awkward or grammatically   incorrect sentence. You can possibly retain the matching text if you put   the link at the end of that information chunk and   then write:
     <ul>
      <li>Refer to <a href="#"> Content formatting <small>Writing guide - WET style guide</small></a>, or </li>
      <li>For further information, refer to: <a href="#"> Content formatting <small>Writing guide - WET style guide</small></a></li>
     </ul>
    </li>
    <li> <strong>the &lt;h1&gt; on the landing page includes text that loses context</strong> when used on another page for example, an InfoZone link titled <a href="http://www.manitobacourts.mb.ca/"> Welcome to Manitoba Courts</a>. It is clearer if the link text is shortened to <a href="http://www.manitobacourts.mb.ca/"> Manitoba Courts</a>, rather than fully matching the &lt;h1&gt; text of the landing page.</li>
    <li> <strong>multiple links on the same page share the same link text, but have different targets</strong>. Distinguish the links by adding more specific link text to them.</li>
   </ul>
   <p>For information on how to format links to  forms or publications, see the guideline on <a href="#form">Forms and publications</a>.</p>
   <h3>Linking descriptive words and phrases</h3>
   <p>You can also introduce a link in screen text in a general way, using descriptive words or phrases. However, <strong>do not include descriptive hyperlinks in documents that will be printed</strong> (for example, letters, forms, and <abbr title="Portable document format">PDF</abbr> documents); rather, provide web addresses in this instance. For more  information on how to format web addresses for print documents, see the  guideline on <a href="#web">web addresses</a>.</p>
   <p>For text that will appear on the web, ensure that you include in a  descriptive hyperlink only the key term or phrase that identifies the  topic.</p>
   <ul>
    <li>You must meet certain criteria to be eligible for the <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/tx/ndvdls/tpcs/ncm-tx/rtrn/cmpltng/ddctns/lns300-350/316/lgbl-eng.html">disability amount</a>. </li>
    <li>Different rules may apply, depending on whether you <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/tx/ndvdls/tpcs/rrsp-reer/cntrbtng/menu-eng.html">contribute to an <abbr title="registered retirement savings plan">RRSP</abbr></a>.</li>
   </ul>
  </div>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="names">Names</h2>
 <p>Use <strong>last name</strong>, rather than <strong>surname</strong> or <strong>family name</strong>. Although <strong>last name</strong> could potentially lead to confusion for some cultural groups, it is the  plainest way to draw this distinction, and it corresponds with <strong>first name</strong>.</p>
 <p>When asking for personal information, do not ask for a <strong>full </strong>name or <strong>full </strong>address. Simply ask for the person's name and address.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="notes">Notes</h2>
 <p>Use notes sparingly to emphasize important information or  exceptions. Make sure you really want to separate the information you  are putting in the note from the rest of your text. If you use too many  notes, or notes that contain too much information, they will lose their  effectiveness.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="numbers">Numbers</h2>
 <p>Spell out numbers for amounts from one through nine. For 10 and  above, use the numeric figure. If a sentence has numbers both higher  and lower than nine, make them all figures. </p>
 <p>Use figures if you are expressing numbers in percentages (for  example, 5%) or in millions, billions, or trillions (for example, 7  million). </p>
 <p>Spell out a number that begins a sentence (or reword the sentence if you want to use a figure).</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <ul>
   <li>Please respond to this report within three days.</li>
   <li>Eleven people are involved in this case.</li>
   <li>There were 2 cases of tax avoidance reported in 15 days.</li>
   <li>Three representatives and 12 accountants responded to our request.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Leave no space between a figure and a dollar sign ($) or a  percentage symbol (%). The dollar sign and any currency notation  precede the figure. The percentage symbol follows the figure.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <ul>
   <li>We raised $1,000 in our charity bake sale. </li>
   <li>Based on today's exchange rate, the amount owing is CAN$732.67.</li>
   <li>Last year, we met our service target 95% of the time.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Large numbers</h3>
 <p>Wherever possible write large numbers using a combination of figures  and words (for example, 14 trillion, 175 million). When using this  combination, use a non-breaking space between the figure and the word. You can create a non-breaking space by pressing, at the same time, the <strong>Ctrl</strong> and <strong>Shift</strong> keys and the <strong>space bar</strong>. </p>
 <p>If you must write large numbers as figures, use commas rather than spaces to separate each group of three digits.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>14,000,000,000,000</li>
   <li>175,000,000</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Numbers: Decimals</h3>
 <p>Use a period to present a number with a decimal.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>The supplies budget shows a deficit of $163.32.</li>
   <li>According to the survey, 85.5% of respondents agreed with our decision.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Numbers: Fractions</h3>
 <p>For simple fractions in text, write out the fraction in words (for example, three-quarters).  For a sentence that contains compound fractions, such as 3 3/4, or a  sentence that mixes compound and simple fractions, use only figures.</p>
 <p>In general, spell out ordinal numbers that can be expressed in one or two words.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>He placed second in the job competition.</li>
   <li>Help us celebrate our fiftieth year in operation. </li>
   <li>We cannot be a twenty-first-century organization with twentieth-century technology.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Use numerical figures for ordinal numbers that would require more than two words if spelled out and for address information. Do not, however, use superscript format. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>We will meet in the boardroom on the 12th floor at 2 <abbr title="after midday">p.m.</abbr> </li>
   <li>Yours was the 225th application we received. </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>For information on how to use numbers to express time, see <a href="#date">Date and time</a>.</p>
 <h3>Numbers: In French</h3>
 <p>Different rules apply when writing numbers in French. For example, in French texts you should:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>use a non-breaking space to separate each group of three digits in a large number; </li>
  <li>use a comma rather than a period to indicate a decimal;</li>
  <li>include a non-breaking space between a number and a percentage symbol (%); </li>
  <li>include a non-breaking space between a number and a dollar sign ($); </li>
  <li>place the dollar sign and any currency notation after the figure; and</li>
  <li>present ordinal numbers using superscript format.</li>
 </ul>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>158 000 d&eacute;clarants &eacute;lectroniques</li>
   <li>50 % du gain en capital</li>
   <li>4,5 millions de dollars</li>
   <li>17,29 %</li>
   <li>163,32 $</li>
   <li>3 225 $US</li>
   <li>175e rang</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="official">Official languages</h2>
 <p>Make sure you produce documents for the <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr> in accordance with the <a href="http://infozone/english/r2732472/ec%2Dce/ol%2Dlo/legpol%2De.asp">policies and directives on official languages</a> and the <em>Official Languages Act</em>. </p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="periodforms" >Periods on forms </h2>
 <p>Follow these guidelines if you draft lines on forms, including returns and schedules.</p>
 <p><strong>Use a period</strong> when it is a single sentence. In general, a sentence is defined as a subject + verb + object, a  subject + verb, or, as on the forms, an imperative verb (add, enter,  use, multiply) followed by an object.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <ul>
   <li>Add lines 400 to 440.</li>
   <li>Enter the amount from line 1 or line 3, whichever is less. </li>
   <li>Multiply line 18 by line 19.</li>
   <li>Add the amounts on line 5 of column 1 and column 2, if applicable.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> use a period when it is a phrase (incomplete sentence). </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <ul>
   <li>Ontario political contributions made in 2008</li>
   <li>Unused risk capital investment tax credits from previous years</li>
   <li>Total of amounts your dependant can claim on lines 5804 to 5840 of his or her Form NT428</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>When a phrase is followed by a sentence, put the sentence between  parentheses and start with a lower case letter. Don't add a period. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <ul>
   <li>Universal child care benefit (see the guide)</li>
   <li>Interest and other investment income (attach Schedule 4)</li>
   <li>Rate (see the note above)</li>
   <li>Line 29 minus line 30 (if negative, enter &ldquo;0&rdquo;)</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>When a sentence is followed by a phrase, put the phrase between parentheses and start with a lower case letter. Add a period. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Example</h3>
  <p>Enter your taxable income (line 260 of your return).</p>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="pronouns">Pronouns and possessive adjectives</h2>
 <p><strong>Personalize your text</strong></p>
 <p>Address your reader directly, using the pronoun <strong>you</strong>. When you refer to the <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr>, use the pronouns <strong>we</strong> or <strong>us</strong>, and when you refer to yourself, use <strong>I</strong> or <strong>me</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Incorrect example</h4>
  <p>Please call <strong>the undersigned</strong> if you have any questions.</p>
  <div class="mrgn-bttm-lg"></div>
  <h4>Correct example</h4>
  <p>Please call <strong>me</strong> if you have any questions.</p>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Avoid gendered language</strong></p>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> use the masculine pronoun <strong>he</strong> to mean <strong>he or she</strong>. Wherever possible, <strong>rewrite</strong> sentences that use gendered pronouns (<strong>he</strong> or <strong>she</strong>) or gendered possessive adjectives (<strong>his</strong> or <strong>her</strong>) by:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>personalizing the subject</li>
  <li>pluralizing the subject</li>
  <li>eliminating the pronoun or possessive adjective</li>
 </ul>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Incorrect example</h4>
  <p><strong>An individual </strong>is responsible for filing <strong>his or her</strong> tax return for each year in which <strong>he or she</strong> owes tax.</p>
  <div class="mrgn-bttm-lg"></div>
  <h4>Correct example</h4>
  <ul>
   <li><strong>You</strong> are responsible for filing <strong>your</strong> tax return for each year in which <strong>you </strong>owe tax. (personalizing the subject)</li>
   <li><strong>Individuals</strong> are responsible for filing <strong>their</strong> tax returns for each year in which <strong>they</strong> owe tax. (pluralizing the subject)</li>
   <li><strong>An individual</strong> is responsible for filing <strong>a</strong> tax return for each year in which tax is payable. (eliminating the pronoun and possessive adjective)</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Plural pronouns and possessive adjectives with singular subjects</strong></p>
 <p>When you don't know whether the subject is a man, a woman, a company, or an entity, you can use <strong><br />
  they</strong> or <strong>them</strong>. In English, there is no singular pronoun that signifies <strong>he or she or it</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Example</h3>
  <ul>
   <li>We will look at all of the facts related to each particular case to ensure that <strong>the taxpayer</strong> receives all of the relief <strong>they</strong> are entitled to.</li>
   <li>If <strong>a registrant</strong> fails to remit <abbr title="Goods and Services Tax">GST/HST</abbr> as required, <strong>they </strong>will be subject to penalties and arrears interest.</li>
   <li>Choose your tax preparer carefully, and check <strong>their </strong>references.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>If you choose to use <strong>they</strong>, <strong>them</strong>, and<strong> their</strong> with singular subjects, <strong>you must use this combination consistently </strong>throughout your document.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="quotation">Quotation marks</h2>
 <p>We use the North American style (with periods and commas placed <strong>before</strong> the closing quotation mark).</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <ul>
   <li>&ldquo;Under the Canadian tax system, the government relies on  taxpayers to pay what they owe,&rdquo; said Michel Dorais, Commissioner of  the <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr>. </li>
   <li>The  data that you enter will prompt one of the following responses:  &ldquo;Registered,&rdquo; &ldquo;Not registered,&rdquo; or &ldquo;Insufficient information entered.&rdquo;</li>
   <li>See line 255, &quot;Northern residents deductions.&quot;</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>Use quotation marks only when you are quoting something. If you want to highlight a term within text, use <a href="#bold">bold</a>:</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Example</h3>
  <p>A <strong>factual resident</strong> has to calculate federal income tax.</p>
 </div>
 <p>You can use quotation marks to identify a title or button to which you are not linking:</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h3 class="mrgn-tp-0 h4">Examples</h3>
  <p>Go to <a href="http://www.cra-arc.gc.ca/esrvc-srvce/tx/ndvdls/myccnt/menu-eng.html">My Account for Individuals</a> and select &quot;Log in&quot; if you have an epass.</p>
 </div>
 <p><strong>Do not</strong> place linked items in quotation marks. </p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="special">Special characters</h2>
 <h3>Special characters: Ampersand (&amp;)</h3>
 <p>The ampersand has  traditionally been used as a space-saving character in tables and  notes, and in business names like Johnson &amp; Johnson and H&amp;R  Block. Except when used as part of an initialism such as SR&amp;ED  (scientific research and experimental development), do not use the  ampersand as a substitute for <strong>and</strong> in documents or organizational titles.</p>
 <h3><strong>Special characters: e.g., i.e.</strong></h3>
 <p>Do not use <strong>e.g.</strong> (the abbreviation for <em>exempli gratia</em><em>,</em> meaning <strong>for example</strong>). Instead, use <strong>for example</strong>, followed by a comma.</p>
 <p>Do not use <strong>i.e. </strong>(the abbreviation for <em>id est</em><em>, </em>meaning <strong>that is</strong>). Instead, use <strong>that is</strong>, followed by a comma.</p>
 <h3 id="no">Special characters: No.</h3>
 <p>Use <strong>No</strong>. and <strong>Nos</strong>. as the abbreviations for number and numbers.</p>
 <h3>Special characters: Percentage (%)</h3>
 <p>To present percentages, use symbols, not written words. Instead of the word <strong>percent</strong>, use <strong>%</strong>.</p>
 <h3>Special characters: etc.</h3>
 <p>The Latin term <strong>et cetera</strong> (etc.) means &ldquo;and other things,&ldquo; &ldquo;and so on,&rdquo; or an equivalent expression. </p>
 <ul>
  <li>Do not use the expression <strong>et cetera</strong>.</li>
  <li>We do not recommend using the abbreviation <strong>etc. </strong>in your written documents. The abbreviation <strong>etc.</strong> suggests that information provided in the enumeration is incomplete, which may confuse your reader.</li>
  <li>When you cannot give all the items, introduce an enumeration with <strong>including</strong> or <strong>such as</strong>. These words imply that you will only give a few items.</li>
  <li>Do not use <strong>etc.</strong> at the end of an enumeration introduced by <strong>including</strong>, <strong>such as</strong>, <strong>for example</strong>, <strong>that is</strong>, or other equivalent expressions.</li>
 </ul>
 <p>However, if you choose to write <strong>etc.</strong>, remember that the abbreviation <strong>etc.</strong>:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>is always preceded by at least two elements;</li>
  <li>is always preceded and followed by a comma, unless it terminates the sentence or is inside parentheses; and</li>
  <li>is never followed by ellipsis points, but always ends with a period.</li>
 </ul>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Examples</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>For their own protection, employees will not, under any circumstance or at any location, fill out questionnaires, forms, etc.</li>
   <li>There  are many factors that can affect the compliance burden over which we  have little influence or control (characteristics of individual  taxpayers, tax law, tax policy, etc.). </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Special characters: Spelling out characters</h3>
 <p>When describing characters required either to be entered or their   use, write out the character and then include it in parentheses   afterwards. </p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <p>Separate each term with a &quot;,&quot; (comma).</p>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="phone">Phone numbers</h2>
 <p>Format both local and long-distance phone numbers that are not toll-free as follows: 514-873-4692.</p>
 <p>If collect calls are accepted, exclude the <strong>1-</strong> before long-distance numbers that are not toll-free. If the caller dials <strong>1-</strong>, he or she will be charged.</p>
 <p>Five area codes beginning with the number <strong>8</strong>&mdash;800, 855, 866, 877, and 888&mdash;are toll-free. Do not, however, refer to them as toll-free. That is, do not use the adverb <a href="#toll">toll free</a> or the compound adjective <strong>toll-free</strong> before or after these numbers.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <p>If you want to negotiate a suitable payment arrangement, please call 1-866-864-5823. </p>
 </div>
 <p>Make sure telephone numbers are not split over two lines of text. </p>
 <p>If you are writing a number that has an extension, include the word <strong>extension</strong> and a number after the telephone number. Use the short form <strong>ext.</strong> only if you do not have room for the full word. Remember, also, to put a comma before the word <strong>extension</strong>.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <p>613-888-8888, extension 5555</p>
 </div>
 <p>Generally, do not introduce telephone numbers with phrases like, &quot;To  get information on this topic, call our general enquiries line at 1-800-959-2221.&quot; Instead, simply say, &quot;To get information on this topic, call 1-800-959-2221.&quot; </p>
 <p>However, if you are providing numbers for more than one area, you will have to decide whether to name each area.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <p>Call our automated Tax Information Phone Service (TIPS) at 1-800-267-6999 or our individual income tax enquiries line at 1-800-959-8281.</p>
 </div>
 <p>In a web document, do not refer readers to a telephone number to  order publications. Link to the document in question or refer readers  to the <strong>Forms and publications</strong> link.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="underline"> Underline</h2>
 <p>Do not use underline text. Underlined text implies a link on a web page.</p>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="web">Web addresses</h2>
 <p>For references to the <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr> website, use <strong>www.cra.gc.ca</strong> (for English text) and <strong>www.arc.gc.ca</strong> (for French text). Whenever possible, however, refer readers to specific webpages on the site.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>For more information about the children's fitness amount, go to <strong>www.cra.gc.ca/fitness</strong>.</li>
   <li>Go to <a href="http://www.cra.gc.ca/leads">www.cra.gc.ca/leads</a> to learn how to report a suspected case of tax evasion.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h3>Web addresses: In print </h3>
 <p>For documents that will be <strong>printed or published in <abbr title="Portable document format">PDF</abbr></strong>, put references to websites or webpages in bold type. Include <strong>www.</strong> but omit <strong>http://</strong></p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Throughout the guide, we refer to other forms and  publications you may need. You can get these forms and publications  from our website at <strong>www.cra.gc.ca/forms</strong> or by calling us at 1-800-959-2221.</li>
   <li>For details, go to <strong>www.cra.gc.ca/electronicservices</strong>.</li>
   <li>Go to <strong>www.cra.gc.ca/benefits-calculator</strong> to use our child and family benefits calculators. </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>If you want to refer readers to a particular topic on a webpage,  provide the address for that page and instruct readers how to navigate  from there.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <p>For more information, go to <strong>www.cra.gc.ca/audit</strong> and select the topic &ldquo;How we select files to audit.&rdquo;</p>
 </div>
 <p>For documents that will be uploaded to the web in <abbr title="Hypertext Markup Language">HTML</abbr>, hyperlink the entire address. Include <strong>www.</strong> but omit <strong>http://</strong>:</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>Throughout the guide, we refer to other forms and publications you may need. You can get these forms and publications at <a href="http://www.cra.gc.ca/forms">www.cra.gc.ca/forms</a> or by calling us at 1-800-959-2221.</li>
   <li>For details, go to <a href="http://www.cra.gc.ca/electronicservices">www.cra.gc.ca/electronicservices</a>.</li>
   <li>Go to <a href="http://www.cra.gc.ca/benefits-calculator">www.cra.gc.ca/benefits-calculator</a> to use our child and family benefits calculators. </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>For more information on hyperlinking web addresses, documents, and descriptive terms, see the guideline on <a href="#links">Links</a>.</p>
 <h3>Web addresses: Punctuation</h3>
 <p>When including a web address at the end of a sentence, put a period  after the address but do not bold the punctuation or include it in the  link format.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>You will find more information about this program on our website at <strong>www.cra.gc.ca</strong>. You can also call our toll-free enquiries line. </li>
   <li>You can get more information about the Community Volunteer Income Tax Program at <a href="http://www.cra.gc.ca/volunteer">www.cra.gc.ca/volunteer</a>. We offer free training sessions to teach you how to fill out basic income tax and benefit returns. </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <p>You can often avoid using punctuation before or after an address by presenting the address in the body of the sentence.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>For more information, visit our website at <strong>www.cra.gc.ca</strong> or call your tax services office. </li>
   <li>Go to <a href="http://www.cra.gc.ca/careers">www.cra.gc.ca/careers</a> to find out more about career opportunities with the <abbr title="Canada Revenue Agency">CRA</abbr>.</li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header"  id="website">Website and webpage references</h2>
 <p>When referring a reader to a website or a webpage in a guide, form, or other document, keep the following in mind:</p>
 <ul>
  <li>A <strong>website</strong> is a collection of webpages. A web address that ends with the primary domain of &quot;gc.ca,&quot; such as <strong>www.cra.gc.ca</strong> and <strong>www.netfile.gc.ca</strong>, indicates a website. When you refer a reader to a website, use the word <strong>visit</strong>. </li>
  <li>A web address that includes a slash and text after the primary domain, such as <strong>www.cra.gc.ca/tfsa</strong> or <strong>www.cra.gc.ca/voluntarydisclosures</strong>, indicates a <strong>webpage</strong>. When you refer a reader to a webpage, use the words <strong>go to</strong>. </li>
 </ul>
 <p><strong>Visiting</strong> a website is dynamic&mdash;you navigate through the multiple pages the site offers. <strong>Going to</strong> a webpage is static&mdash;you expect to find what you are looking for on the referenced page.</p>
 <div class="well">
  <h4 class="mrgn-tp-0">Example</h4>
  <ul>
   <li>For more information, visit <strong>www.cra.gc.ca</strong>. </li>
   <li>For details on our e-services, go to <strong>www.cra.gc.ca/electronicservices</strong>. </li>
  </ul>
 </div>
 <h2 class="page-header" id="terminology"> Web terminology</h2>
 <p>This list of terms is a guide for ensuring words are spelled consistently.</p>
 <ul>
  <li><strong>Internet</strong> Initial caps</li>
  <li><strong>intranet</strong> All lowercase</li>
  <li><strong>Web</strong> The word web is only capitalized when it is used in a proper name, such as World Wide Web.</li>
  <li><strong>website</strong> Two words, lowercase.</li>
  <li><strong>web application</strong> Two words, lowercase.</li>
  <li><strong>web page</strong> Two words, lowercase.</li>
  <li><strong>web form</strong> Two words, lowercase.</li>
  <li><strong>Note:</strong> Initial caps and bold.</li>
  <li><strong>email</strong> No hyphen, not e-mail.</li>
 </ul>
 <h2 class="page-header"  id="resources">External resources</h2>
 <h3>Dictionaries</h3>
 <p>We use the <em>Canadian Oxford Dictionary</em> as our principal  reference on matters of spelling and word use. If it lists more than  one spelling for a word, we normally choose the first one listed. See  the following for other references on spelling and word use: </p>
 <ul>
